item.title: A List Apart: Articles: Responsive Comping: Obtaining Signoff with Mockups
item.dc:creator: digimindshare
item.description: If you’re making websites, chances are you’ve given some thought to what constitutes a responsive-friendly design process—and you’ve probably found that adding a mockup for every breakpoint isn’t a sustainable approach. Designing in code sounds like the answer, but you may be mystified at where to begin—or feel unmoored and disoriented at the prospect of giving up the approach you’ve long relied on. Enter responsive comping. This new, mockup-less web design process makes it easy to get that Photoshop monkey off your back, and have a fresh new beginning with your old friend the web browser.

item.title: A List Apart: Articles: The Infinite Grid
item.dc:creator: digimindshare
item.description: Grid systems are a key component of graphic design, but they’ve always been designed for canvases with fixed dimensions. Until now. Today you’re designing for a medium that has no fixed dimensions, a medium that can and will shape-shift to better suit its environment—a medium capable of displaying a single layout on a smartphone, a billboard in Times Square, and everything in between. You’re designing for an infinite canvas—and for that, you need an infinite grid system. Discover techniques and guidelines that can help bring structure to your content whatever the screen size.

item.title: Check the Weather
item.dc:creator: kevinmichaelkeating
item.description: The interface of Check the Weather is intentionally simple. It provides just the data you need, without any distractions or confusion. Accurate — Built on top of some of the most advanced weather forecasting systems available, Check the Weather gives hyper-accurate data wherever you find yourself. Fast — Check the Weather is optimized from the ground up to be fast and fluid, whether you are on the fanciest new iPhone or a more vintage model. Beautiful — From its thoughtfully laid out information hierarchy to its extensive use of custom typography, Check the Weather is designed to make you want to open it. Layered — The app presents a beguilingly simple interface. All the basic weather data is immediately presented on the home dashboard. A simple swipe left, right or up exposes detailed drill-down data providing everything a budding meteorologist could want.

item.title: Open Data Structures: an open content textbook
item.dc:creator: kai.zee
item.description:
Open Data Structures covers the implementation and analysis of data structures for sequences (lists), queues, priority queues, unordered dictionaries, ordered dictionaries, and graphs.
Data structures presented in the book include stacks, queues, deques, and lists implemented as arrays and linked-lists; space-efficient implementations of lists; skip lists; hash tables and hash codes; binary search trees including treaps, scapegoat trees, red-black trees, binary tries, x-fast tries, and y-fast tries; heaps, including implicit binary heaps and randomized meldable heaps; and graphs, including adjacency matrix and ajacency list representations.

item.title: Tweetbot for Mac — Tapbots
item.dc:creator: josephschmitt
item.description:
from Daring Fireball
When a great iPhone app comes out, it’s easy to ask the developer to expand it to the iPad too, and then bring it to the Mac. You know what’s hard? Actually doing it. But Tapbots has done it with Tweetbot. $20 for a Twitter client? Damn straight. Screw the race to the bottom. I’m happy to pay for quality work.
For more, see Rene Ritchie’s iMore interview with Tapbots developer Todd Thomas and designer Mark Jardine.
★
